    '{"label":"positive","confidence":0.95,"bullets":["Resolved Zoom integration issue caused by a recently added required question in workflow.","Enabled public access to shared lists, unblocking internal reviews and Salesforce mapping.","Confirmed landing page forms are functional; team aligned on kickoff readiness for Monday.","Client approved Q1 budget increase; additional funds to address project backlog and scoring.","Newsletter template deployed in HubSpot; coordinator now cloning for multiple product lines."],"highlights":[{"quote":"We don''t like to owe money and two, let''s find out how to level up.","speaker":"bwillans"},{"quote":"We''re turning it on. We''re all on the same page here.","speaker":"Colin Costigan"},{"quote":"We couldn''t be happier.","speaker":"bwillans"}],"topics":["integration","delivery","budget","scoring"],"model":"openai/gpt-4-1106-preview","version":1,"generated_at":"2026-01-16T00:00:00Z"}'::jsonb,
    '{"fireflies_summary":{"notes":"## **Salesforce and HubSpot Integration**\n\nThe team is finalizing Salesforce integration with lead lists and HubSpot data flow to streamline contact management and scoring.\n\n- **Kyle''s access issue to lead lists delayed review, but the lists impressed his team once accessible, prompting a shift to public visibility for all three lists** (04:01)  \n    - Kyle will immediately review the lists once access is granted.  \n    - Colin emphasized clarifying duplicated data fields like segments and product brands to ensure accurate record matching.  \n    - Barb acknowledged database inconsistencies but expects Kyle’s review to confirm usability.  \n    - The integration will proceed once Kyle approves the lists, ensuring clean data transfer.\n\n- **HubSpot contact properties now pull from specific dropdown sources to maintain data consistency across customer community and sales outreach segments** (06:25)  \n    - Barb confirmed the team agrees with this approach after seeing the setup.  \n    - Guille reported the landing page with two forms is live, but inconsistent sales rep name formatting needs alignment before Monday’s kickoff.  \n    - Colin committed to fixing formatting and removing a fully embedded input lead form immediately to prevent confusion.  \n    - These updates ensure contacts are accurately tied to accounts in HubSpot, supporting targeted outreach.\n\n- **A Zoom integration issue broke workflow due to a newly added required question, but the team quickly fixed it, preventing further data loss** (08:32)  \n    - Barb learned not to add required questions retroactively to avoid breaking flows.  \n    - The fix restored correct data reflection in dashboards, improving event tracking accuracy.\n\n- **Newsletter templates built in HubSpot are fully customizable and delegated to the new coordinator, enabling faster cloning and deployment across product lines** (09:22)  \n    - Barb confirmed the coordinator is familiar with HubSpot and ready to manage newsletter cloning and edits.  \n    - This delegation accelerates content distribution and reduces bottlenecks in marketing communications.\n\n## **Lead Scoring Development and Prioritization**\n\nLead scoring logic is under construction to enable better sales qualification, with a clear plan to address backlog and prioritize key segments.\n\n- **No leads have been scored yet, but uploaded contacts from recent webinars are ready for scoring to start manual outreach by BDRs next week** (10:55)  \n    - Barb explained that scoring over 100 points does not automatically push leads to Salesforce yet; manual calls are expected initially.  \n    - Colin detailed that HubSpot scoring rules now exclude internal companies from progressing beyond Prospect status, refining lead quality.  \n    - The ICP fit score and other criteria are being built out progressively to reflect the detailed logic Barb provided.  \n    - This phased scoring approach balances automation with manual sales effort while the system matures.\n\n- **Barb requested clarity on managing negative lead scores and emphasized the need to clear current backlog points owed to the agency** (12:46)  \n    - She confirmed a **$10,000/month Q1 budget** is approved but highlighted a small January refund issue that delayed payments.  \n    - Vivian supports increasing funding by an additional **$6,000** to clear backlog and accelerate priority projects like ABM for mining and Food & Beverage segments.  \n    - Barb wants to front-load spending for February and March to enable faster delivery and testing of these key initiatives.  \n    - This funding adjustment is seen as critical to maintaining momentum and meeting Q1 goals.\n\n- **Tristan outlined coordinating a simple addendum for increasing Q1 budget to avoid disrupting ongoing weekly work** (17:02)  \n    - Barb agreed to prioritize defining backlog costs and next steps before finalizing the addendum.  \n    - She confirmed availability for a short meeting next week to align on priorities and confirm payment details.  \n    - This approach keeps core work flowing while enabling increased resource allocation for critical tasks.\n\n## **Account Management and Client Relationship**\n\nStrong collaboration and trust between the agency and client are enabling steady progress despite challenges.\n\n- **Barb praised the agency for never dropping the ball and maintaining consistent delivery over the past three months** (20:44)  \n    - She contrasted this with other affiliates struggling with HubSpot adoption and integration.  \n    - Vivian’s pragmatic, no-perfectionist attitude helps keep projects moving without getting stuck on minor issues.  \n    - Tristan emphasized the strong team dynamic and client responsiveness as key to success.  \n    - Barb frequently recommends the agency to other affiliates, reinforcing long-term partnership value.\n\n- **Barb expressed concern about financial arrears and stressed the importance of timely payments to maintain trust** (13:58)  \n    - She highlighted issues with HubSpot shutting off accounts despite payments, praising the agency for avoiding such disruptions.  \n    - The client wants to avoid owing money and prefers upfront budgeting and clear funding plans.  \n    - This financial transparency supports a stable working relationship and prioritizes clearing backlog promptly.\n\n- **Plans were made to schedule a focused meeting Tuesday at 3:00 PM Eastern to finalize backlog clearance and prioritize Q1 deliverables** (23:08)  \n    - Barb will lead the conversation with support from Colin, Tristan, and possibly Kyle for clarifications.  \n    - This meeting aims to lock in budget, backlog scope, and project sequencing for the rest of Q1.  \n    - The goal is to ensure all parties are aligned and ready for the upcoming product launches and ABM testing.\n\n## **ABM and Product Priorities**\n\nThe team is focusing on Account-Based Marketing (ABM) and microsite development as critical for Q1, with clear resource allocation plans.\n\n- **Barb identified ABM for mining and Food & Beverage as the highest priority projects for February and March, targeting Q1 testing and rollout** (16:33)  \n    - Vivian supports dedicating increased funding and agency effort to these segments given their strategic value.  \n    - Barb noted some microsite landing pages for video hosting could be handled internally by James if agency points run low.  \n    - This prioritization reflects a focused approach to deliver high-impact campaigns within limited time and budget.  \n    - The team aims to start testing ABM by end of Q1 to gather early feedback and optimize.\n\n- **Tristan committed to managing workload boundaries and coordinating between weekly tasks and priority projects to avoid overloading Colin and Guille** (18:07)  \n    - He will handle communications with Barb and Vivian on budgeting and scope changes separately from daily project calls.  \n    - This division of responsibilities helps keep core work on track while enabling flexible scaling of resources for critical initiatives.  \n    - The approach minimizes context switching and supports focused execution.\n\n- **Hawk integration remains an affiliate-driven initiative with no direct agency involvement but close monitoring due to shared referrals and reputation** (18:50)  \n    - Barb reported positive endorsements for the agency from affiliates despite some not currently using the service.  \n    - The agency is positioned as a trusted resource and potential partner for Hawk-related CRM decisions expected in Q1 or Q2.  \n    - This relationship may open future collaboration opportunities and expands agency visibility in the affiliate network.\n\n## **Process Improvements and Workflow Stability**\n\nContinuous learning and quick fixes are improving workflows and reducing downtime risks.\n\n- **Zoom integration failure was traced to a required question added after the initial setup, underscoring the need for change management** (08:32)  \n    - Barb acknowledged the importance of finalizing form questions before workflow activation to prevent breakage.  \n    - The quick fix restored data correctness and dashboard accuracy, avoiding long-term tracking gaps.  \n    - This incident highlighted tighter controls on form adjustments moving forward.\n\n- **Lead form updates and newsletter template deployment demonstrate improved operational flexibility and user experience** (09:22)  \n    - Drag-and-drop newsletter modules allow non-technical coordinators to make edits and clone content easily.  \n    - Lead form adjustments on the landing page will remove unused forms and standardize fields for better data capture.  \n    - These updates reduce bottlenecks and empower internal teams to manage content dynamically.  \n    - The improvements contribute to smoother marketing execution and faster response cycles.\n\n- **Clear escalation and communication protocols ensure high transparency and responsiveness between client and agency** (12:46)  \n    - Barb and Colin maintain close contact to avoid arrears and resolve payment issues quickly.  \n    - Tristan’s role includes managing scope, prioritization, and resource allocation to keep projects aligned with client budgets.  \n    - This structure reduces risk of miscommunication and supports steady progress despite evolving demands.  \n    - The team’s responsiveness is a key factor in client satisfaction and project momentum.","outline":null,"keywords":["Lead Scoring","HubSpot Integration","Salesforce","ABM Tool","Budget Addendum","Affiliate Onboarding"],"overview":"- **Salesforce Integration:** Lead lists delayed review; once approved, transition to public visibility for accuracy in data management.\n\n- **HubSpot Consistency:** Contact properties now use dropdowns to maintain data accuracy; sales rep names need formatting fixes before kickoff.\n\n- **Budget Allocation:** Approved $10,000/month Q1 budget, seeking additional $6,000 to clear backlog and prioritize important projects.\n\n- **ABM Priorities:** Focus on mining and Food & Beverage projects for Q1; testing to start by end of March for effective rollout.\n\n- **Process Improvements:** Zoom integration failure highlighted change management needs; quick fixes are enhancing workflow stability and data accuracy.\n\n- **Communication Protocols:** Close contact between client and agency to resolve issues quickly; clear role divisions support project alignment and progress.","action_items":"\n**Colin Costigan**\nChange all three contact lists from private to public and notify Kyle for review (04:01)\nCorrect sales rep name formatting on Hawk and OTT web forms for consistency (08:27)\nMake changes on landing page forms as discussed (08:27)\nContinue building out lead scoring logic and integrate scoring rules based on Barb’s input (10:16)\nKeep lead scoring updated and prepare for integration when contact lists are approved (24:50)\n\n**Barb Willans**\nInform Kyle to review public contact lists and report any changes (04:06)\nCheck with Kyle on sales rep name formatting preference (07:26)\nMonitor and manage scoring process; coordinate manual outreach with BDRs until full automation (10:55)\nCoordinate discussion with Vivian regarding budget priorities and addendum for Q1 backlog and next quarter funding (14:38)\nConfirm availability for Tuesday 3:00 pm Eastern meeting to finalize backlog and priorities (23:18)\n\n**Tristan Pelligrino**\nSupport communication on budget addendum options and Q1 front-loading process with Barb and Vivian (18:07)\nSchedule and lead follow-up meeting with Barb to discuss backlog clearing and priorities (22:46)\nAssist with Hawk affiliate outreach as needed and coordinate internal team focus (18:07)\n\n**Guille Santana**\nRefresh and update landing page forms as requested and fix ''check your data health'' label on Hawk form (07:26)\n"},"migrated_from":"contract_meetings","